We need a completed Xcode build to open the project in Xcode. The recovery instructions seem pretty clear, if you can pause the video at just the right moment.

@jmagman Do you know if Xcode has changed its default profiles? This user has three debug profiles but none have the name expected by flutter_tool. LMK if I should transfer this to flutter/flutter.
I wouldn't expect it to run anything and just give me an error? You can see in the video it tried to build it rather than an error?
@cadaniel Did you try the suggested remedy? It is printed in red text in the video.

The error is actually I have custom schemes in the iOS project. 

I knew I needed open the Xcode project, and that's what I was trying to do. I had to open a swift file and use that link instead.
That's awesome! I don't care that the build failed, I just wanted to open straight to Xcode.

Also I don't buy the Xcode wasn't set up enough to open Xcode. Because switching to a .swift file and opening using the same link worked, and the bug still happened even after Xcode was actually already open.

> Also I don't buy the Xcode wasn't set up enough to open Xcode. Because switching to a .swift file and opening using the same link worked, and the bug still happened even after Xcode was actually already open.

I mean, it'll open, but it won't actually build in Xcode unless you (or your IDE) run `flutter build ios` at least once to populate the Xcode build settings.  It worked for you because the IDE did that for you and populated the build settings.  You can run `flutter clean` then `open ios/Runner.xcworkspace` and see for yourself.

 If you're using schemes, you're probably better off using the command line so you can pass in your flavor names.

The problem is it didn't open. I had to go to a different file to open Xcode. 

I know flutter needs to build first, but I'm chasing some unrelated Xcode madness to test some iOS specific features.

> The problem is it didn't open. I had to go to a different file to open Xcode.

Just open the project directly in Xcode, `open ios/Runner.xcworkspace`.

That's still harder. 

The point is why did it work on a swift file and not Podfile

> @stevemessick there's a new flutter build ios --config-only flag flutter/flutter#64848 available in 1.22.0-12.0.pre which will set up the Xcode project, but not actually compile anything.

Thanks @jmagman ! I did not know about that. We'll use that instead.

@cadaniel wrote:
> The error is actually I have custom schemes in the iOS project.

Exactly. The flutter command line tool doesn't know how to use your custom schemes. If you want to make things work for you now just perform the steps needed by the command line tool. If you do not want to perform those steps then you will continue to see this error.

Future work tracked in #5411
